  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When sellers talk about getting their property valued, they often mean something quite different from what the term formally refers to in Queensland. A real estate agent can give you an appraisal of what your property is likely to sell for in the current market. A registered valuer provides a formal valuation, which is a legally recognised opinion of market value prepared by a credentialled professional. The two documents serve different purposes, are produced by different people, and carry different legal weight. Understanding the distinction matters because there are situations where only a formal valuation will do.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Agent appraisals versus formal valuations</h2>
      <p>An agent's appraisal is an informed estimate, not a regulated document. A licensed real estate agent uses their knowledge of comparable sales, current market conditions, and the specific features of your property to arrive at a range they believe represents likely sale value. It is the foundation of good campaign strategy and pricing, and a skilled agent who knows their market well will give you a figure that is genuinely useful. But an appraisal is not a formal valuation, and it cannot be used for legal, financial, or tax purposes that require a certified document.</p>

      <p>A formal property valuation in Queensland can only be prepared by a registered valuer, as required under the Valuers Registration Act 1992. Registered valuers are trained and credentialled professionals who assess a property's market value using a structured methodology, apply comparable sales analysis under professional standards, and produce a report that carries legal standing. They carry professional indemnity insurance and their work is subject to scrutiny in courts, by the Australian Taxation Office, and by financial institutions.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When Queensland sellers need a formal valuation</h2>
      <p>Most straightforward residential sales do not require a formal valuation at all. If you are selling your home, an agent appraisal is sufficient for pricing decisions. The situations where sellers need a formal valuation are specific and often arise outside the normal sale transaction.</p>

      <p>Deceased estates are the most common case. When a property is part of a deceased estate, a formal valuation is typically required to establish the date-of-death value for capital gains tax purposes and, in some cases, for fair distribution among beneficiaries. The Australian Taxation Office requires a credentialled valuation for CGT calculations, not an agent appraisal.</p>

      <p>Family law proceedings require a formal valuation when property is being divided as part of a property settlement. The Family Court will not accept an agent's estimate as the basis for determining property interests. Both parties typically instruct their own valuers, and where there is disagreement, a single joint expert may be appointed.</p>

      <p>Self-managed superannuation funds must obtain an independent formal valuation when acquiring or disposing of residential property. The ATO requires valuations from a qualified and independent professional, and an SMSF trustee who relies on an agent appraisal for these transactions risks compliance issues.</p>

      <p>Capital gains tax calculations on investment properties also require a formal valuation in some circumstances, particularly when determining the market value at the date a property was first used to produce income or when a partial main residence exemption is being calculated.</p>

      <p>Dispute resolution processes, whether through a court, a tribunal, or a mediation process, will require formal valuations as evidence of market value.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How bank valuations work and why sellers have no control</h2>
      <p>When a buyer is obtaining finance to purchase your property, their lender will typically order their own valuation of the property before approving the loan. This is the bank valuation, and it is done for the bank's benefit, not yours. The lender wants to confirm that the security for the loan is worth at least as much as the amount being borrowed. You as the seller have no say in who the bank chooses as its valuer, no access to the valuation report, and no formal right to dispute it.</p>

      <p>Bank valuers are generally conservative. Their job is to protect the lender from the risk that the property is worth less than the loan amount. They do not give you the benefit of emotional value or perceived scarcity. They apply a market value methodology based on recent comparable sales and will sometimes come in below the price a motivated buyer has agreed to pay in a competitive campaign. In Brisbane's inner east, where well-presented properties can attract emotionally driven bidding that pushes prices above recent comparables, a bank valuation shortfall is not unusual.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens when a bank valuation comes in below the contract price</h2>
      <p>A shortfall between the bank's assessed value and the contract price creates a finance gap. If the buyer was borrowing based on the contract price and the bank will only lend against a lower figure, the buyer needs to cover the difference from their own funds or renegotiate the contract. This is one of the more stressful situations in a Queensland property sale, and it happens more frequently when markets have run hard and prices have moved ahead of the comparable sales data that valuers rely on.</p>

      <p>The buyer has a few options. They can make up the shortfall from savings or other equity, proceed with the purchase and accept a reduced loan-to-value ratio, request a review of the valuation by providing additional comparable sales evidence, or seek a second valuation from a different lender and use that result. They can also attempt to renegotiate the contract price with the seller, though there is no obligation on the seller to accept a lower price because the buyer's bank has assessed it conservatively.</p>

      <p>As a seller, your options are limited. You can provide your agent's comparable sales evidence to help the buyer's case for a review, but you cannot directly challenge the bank's valuation. In practice, the most useful thing you can do is work with your agent to support the buyer in gathering sales evidence that reflects the true market. Your agent should have recent comparable transactions that support the contract price. Whether the bank's valuer accepts that evidence is outside your control.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Planning ahead to reduce the risk of a shortfall</h2>
      <p>There is no guaranteed way to prevent a bank valuation shortfall, but sellers and agents can take steps that reduce the risk. Pricing a campaign within a range that is clearly supported by recent comparable sales reduces the chance that a buyer's emotional bidding pushes the price into territory a bank valuer will not follow. Providing your agent with a clear evidence file of the best recent comparable sales in your suburb gives them the tools to support any review process that a buyer initiates.</p>

      <p>In a market where values have moved fast and recent comparable sales are limited, it is worth discussing the valuation risk explicitly with your agent before launching. Understanding whether the price range you are targeting is supportable by the available evidence will help you set expectations for what happens if a buyer's finance becomes complicated.</p>

